description: {"blocks":[{"key":"al89","text":"This protocol describes steps to prepare non-fixed, fresh frozen tissue that has been embedded in OCT, CMC or other embedding material.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5gqi7","text":"The protocol has been used in preparation for DARTFISH and MERFISH assays, as well as for representative serial section H\u0026E stains of the tissue blocks used in these assays.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"8bp83","text":"Slides may be stored (briefly) at -80  but it is thought to be better to use or, if needed, ship on dry ice, within 24-48 hours of sectioning ","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Tissue Processing – Cutting Fresh Frozen Lung Sections for FISH
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"6r86l","text":"Prepare the SuperFrost Plus slides by placing them into a staining rack.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Tissue Processing – Cutting Fresh Frozen Lung Sections for FISH
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"9b8ok","text":"Rinse the slides with ultrapure water and spray them with RNaseZAP, allowing them to sit for a few minutes.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Tissue Processing – Cutting Fresh Frozen Lung Sections for FISH
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"6ad9i","text":"Rinse the slides with more ultrapure water and, while keeping them in the slide rack, dry them on the slide warmer for about 20 minutes. Keep preparing the cryostat during this time.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Tissue Processing – Cutting Fresh Frozen Lung Sections for FISH
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"9ejaa","text":"Spray the inside of the cryostat with RNaseZAP and after 3 minutes wipe down the inside with 100% ethanol making sure the chamber is dry.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Tissue Processing – Cutting Fresh Frozen Lung Sections for FISH
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"c725i","text":"Place a new blade into the chamber and allow to cool for 5 minutes. During this time, place the tissue block to be sectioned onto the chuck, or aside in the cryostat chamber if cutting more than one, and allow them to equilibrate to the cryostat chamber temperature","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Tissue Processing – Cutting Fresh Frozen Lung Sections for FISH
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"17t6u","text":"Place the sample (example, fresh frozen embedded in OCT, stored at -80) to be cut on the chuck and trim until a full section can be cut.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Tissue Processing – Cutting Fresh Frozen Lung Sections for FISH
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"ut2p","text":"Cut sections at the desired thickness, generally 10 micron, and place the section onto a room temperature treated coverglass.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}},{"key":"5qoo6","text":"","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Tissue Processing – Cutting Fresh Frozen Lung Sections for FISH
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"fmiap","text":"Pipette 50 µL of water from the 15 mL conical onto the correctly labeled slide for the section.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Tissue Processing – Cutting Fresh Frozen Lung Sections for FISH
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"1jtbh","text":"Place the section with the TISSUE SIDE UP onto the slide. Place into the cryostat to allow the water to freeze, adhering the section to the slide.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Tissue Processing – Cutting Fresh Frozen Lung Sections for FISH
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"a9d4l","text":"Place the slide into a slidebox on dry ice or in the chamber until finished.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Tissue Processing – Cutting Fresh Frozen Lung Sections for FISH
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"l3ke","text":"SWITCH BLADES BETWEEN DONORS to prevent contamination of nuclei/cell material between donors.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Tissue Processing – Cutting Fresh Frozen Lung Sections for FISH
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"fq7hf","text":"Repeat until finished, keeping slides frozen throughout. Place slides in slide box equilibrated to temperature in the cryostat chamber.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

{"blocks":[{"key":"1bt84","text":"Analysis of RNA quality of the tissue being sectioned can be achieved by isolating RNA from 2 – 20 µm tissue sections and testing for RIN and DV200.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Tissue Processing - Cutting Frozen Tissue Curls for Single Nuclei Isolation
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"bqvlf","text":"Label cryovials appropriate for the tissue section curls to be cut","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Tissue Processing - Cutting Frozen Tissue Curls for Single Nuclei Isolation
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"22qat","text":"Spray the inside of the cryostat with RNaseZAP and after 3 minutes wipe down the inside with 100% ethanol making sure the chamber is dry.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Tissue Processing - Cutting Frozen Tissue Curls for Single Nuclei Isolation
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"foj7s","text":"Place a new blade into the chamber and allow to cool for 5 minutes. During this time, place the tissue block to be sectioned onto the chuck, or aside in the cryostat chamber if cutting more than one, and allow them to equilibrate to the cryostat chamber temperature","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Tissue Processing - Cutting Frozen Tissue Curls for Single Nuclei Isolation
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"bch6o","text":"Place the sample (example, fresh frozen embedded in OCT, stored at -80) to be cut on the chuck and trim until a full section can be cut.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Tissue Processing - Cutting Frozen Tissue Curls for Single Nuclei Isolation
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"83opq","text":"Cut the tissue sections for sn isolation at the desired thickness, generally 40 micron, allowing the tissue to curl. Gently recover tissue curl into a labelled cryovial.  May place up to ~ 10 curls into a 1.5 ml cryovial. The thickness and number of sections collected per tissue block will depend on tissue type, density and desired yield.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Tissue Processing - Cutting Frozen Tissue Curls for Single Nuclei Isolation
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"big2","text":"Approximately every 10 thick section, cut 1 or 2 full face, serial 10 micron sections on SuperFrost Plus slides  to stain with H\u0026E to demonstrate morphology of the tissue being collected for sn isolation.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Tissue Processing - Cutting Frozen Tissue Curls for Single Nuclei Isolation
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"9ngmd","text":"SWITCH BLADES BETWEEN DONORS to prevent contamination of nuclei/cell material between donors.","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}

steps.section: Tissue Processing - Cutting Frozen Tissue Curls for Single Nuclei Isolation
steps.step: {"blocks":[{"key":"7s03c","text":"Cryovials containing cryosectioned tissue curls may be shipped on dry ice","type":"unstyled","depth":0,"inlineStyleRanges":[],"entityRanges":[],"data":{}}],"entityMap":{}}
